TRAP
ACCIDENT
IN
BOTCHERGATE.—On
Sunday

afternoon
as
a
trap
belonging
to
Mr.
H.
Miller,
Grey

stone,
containing
Mr.
H.
Miller,
jun.,
and
two
friends

was
being
driven
up
Botchergate,
one
of
the
wheels

suddenly
came
off
and
the
occupants
were
pitched

heavily
on
to
the
pavement,
but
fortunately
without

sustaining
serious
injury
beyond
a
bruise
on
Mr.

Miller's
knee.
The
horse
bolted
and
galloped
up

Botchergate,
with
the
axle
trailing
on
the
ground,
and

reached
Portland
Place
before
it
was
stopped.

ZENANA
WORK
IN
INDIA.—On
Tuesday
evening
an

address
on
missionary
work
among
the
Zenanas
of

India
was
given
in
the
Lecture
Hall,
Fisher
Street,
by

Miss
Matthews,
who
has
laboured
for
some
years
118

medical
missionary
in
that
land.
Mr
J.
N.
Carr

presided,

among
those
present
were
Mr
Redmayne

and
the
Rev.
Owen
K.
Hobbs.

latter
opened
the

meeting
with
prayer.
The
speaker
stated
that
six

years
ago
she
sailed
for
India

her

of

now.

graphic
description
of
her

experiences;
and
appealed
for
help
on

of
the

Hindoo
women,

she
stated
were
denied
male

medical
assistance
and
male
society,
and
kept
in
a

state
of
ignorance.
At
the
close
of
the
meeting,
a
col

lection

aid
of
Zenana
Mission
Work
was

about
£4
being
realised.

STAILE-BOWKETT
BUILDING
SOCIETY.—A
meeting

for
the
purpose
of
founding
one
of
these
societies
in

Carlisle,
was
held
in
the
Co-operative
Hall,
Botcher

gate,
on
Monday
night.
Mr
J.
H.
Ryley
presided,
and

there
was
a
small
attendance.
Mr
R.
B.
Starr,
of

London,
the
founder
of
these
societies,
gave
an
address

on
their
economy,
management,
rules,
and
balloting.

This
would
be
the
167th
that
he
would
have
had
the

pleasure
of
assisting
to
establish.
They
were
in
reality

societies
for
the
promotion
of
thrift,
self-help,
and

independence
among
the
working
classes.
The
speaker

criticised
unfavourably
all
existing
building
societies,

which,
he
said,
were
not
working
men's
societie,s.
Mr

Starr
read
a
number
of
balance
sheets
proving
that
the

Starr-Bowkett
societies
were
flourishing
throughout
the

United
Kingdom,
and
especially
in
London.
Ile
urged

the
necessity
of
working
men
being
thrifty,
and
not

spending
their
money
on
tobacco
and
drink.
He
him

self
had
been
a
teetotaller
for
59
years.
Ladies
also

could
participate
in
the
advantages
of
the
societies.

Directly
an
unmarried
lady
got
a
ballot
she
was
sure
to

get
a
husband,
and
he
would
advise
her
to
keep
all

property
in
her
own
hands,
which
the
law
now
allowed

her
to
do.
He
invited
all
who
wished
to
become
mem

bers
to
remain
behind,
and
join
the
society.

LIFE
SAVING
BELTS.—A
LOCAL
INVENTOR.—MT

John
C.
Purvis,
of
24,
Broad
Street,
in
this
city,
has

recently
invented
two
life-saving
belts
for
the
use
of

travellers
on
the
ocean.
No.
1
is
an
ingenuous
con

truction
made
of
bamboo
cane,
coupled
together

with
india
rubber
rings
and
straps,
which
ensures
a

complete
fit
to
any
person
of
broad
or
narrow
width
of

chest
when
adjusted,
which
is
the
work
of
a
few
seconds

only.
The
belt
takes
a
firm
grip
of
the
body,

and
is
not
liable
to
slip,
and
can
easily
be
made
to
fit

women
and
children.
The
inventor
has
severely
tested

the
efficacy
of
the
belts
by
keeping
them
under
water
for

thirty-six
hours
by
means
of
heavy
weights,
and
when

released
they
have
been
found
perfectly
bound
and
true,

retaining
the
same
floating
power.
The
belts
appear

to
be
very
strong
and
durable,
and
not
easily
put
out
of

order.
No.
2
belt
is
constructed
of
a
number
of
air-tight

floats,
made
of
tin,
zinc,
or
copper,
put
on
straps
of

leather '
woven,
or
elastic
belting.
In
company
with

several
friends,
the
inventor,
clad
in
a
suit
of
clothes
for

the
occasion,
visited
the
Public
Baths,
and
jumped

from
the
diving
stage
into
the
deep
water.
The
No.
1

belt
which
he
wore
soon
proved
to
answer
its
purpose

admirably,
and
the
wearer
was
quite
unable,
when
once

in
the
water,
to
get
his
head
beneath
the
surfs
ce.
No.

2
belt
was
also
tested,
with
the
same
satisfactory

results.
A
provisional
protection
has
been
taken
out.

OUTBREAK
OF
PLEURO

PNEUMONIA
AT
ULVERSTON.

HEAD
OF
CATTLE
SLAUGHTERED.

A
serious
outbreak
of
pleuro-pheumonia
has

oceured
on
the
farm
of
Mr
Barton,
of
Ulverston.

70
head
of
cattle
have
been
slaughtered.—Several
out

breaks
of
pleuro-pneumonia
are
reported
from
Scotland,

and
it
is
alleged
that
the
cattle
came
from
Cumberland.

Mr
Anstruther,
an
inspector
from
the
Board
of
Agri

culture,
has
been
in
the
county
investigating
the
recent

cases
of
pleuro,

that
he
can
make
a
report
to
the
Board.

THE
WEEKLY
HALF-HOLIDAY
MOVEMENT.

GREAT
EXCITEMENT.

The
rumours
circulated
the
last
day
or
so
that
some

of
the
tradesmen
were
going
back
on
their
bargain,
and

intended
to
keep
open
on
Thursday,
unfortunately

proved
too
true.
At
half-past
twelve
the
released

assistants
poured
in
a
body
to
the
shop
fronts
of
Mr

James
Atkinson
and
Messrs
Atkinson
and
Wood,
two

firms
who
had
hitherto
joined
in
the
movement,
but
on

Thursday
announced
that
they
should
keep
open
till
four

o'clock.
Standing
there,
the
crowd
which
stretched

across
the
street,
and
was
chiefly
composed
of
dress

makers
and
shop
assistants,
hooted,
hissed,
and
yelled.

Between
Bank
Street
and
the
Viaduct,
a
couple
of

sandwich
men
kept
walking
to
and
fro,
bearing
boards

with
the
familiar
inscription,
"Please
don't
shop
on

Thursday
afternoons."

About
two
o'clock
the
crowd
began
to
thicken
and
by

half-past
fully
500
people
had
assembled
on
the
pave

ment.
The
newspaper
boys
took
to
the
bill
distributing

with
heartiness,
and
every
passing
carriage
received

quite
a
shower
of
leaflets.
But
the
"observed
of
all

observers"
was
an
effigy
of
"Ally
Sloper."
The
figure

was
mounted
on
two
blocks
of
wood,
bearing
the

appropriate
words
Ally
Sloper's
half-holiday."
This

was
borne
on
the
shoulders
of
a
youth,
who
marched

along
the
channel,
and
as
he
passed
the
doors
of
the

shops
that
were
open
•
'
Ally
"
gracefully
bowed
to
the

occupants,
amid
the
cheers,
yells
and
hisses
of
the
crowd.

A
sergeant
and
the
chief
constable
now
arrived
on

the
scene,
and
the
youth
was
warned
to
take
himself

off.
Refusing
to
do
this,
the
chief
constable
ordered
his

arrest,
and
he
was
marched
to
the
police
station
by
a

constable,
the
sergeant
bearing
poor
"
Sloper."
At

the
top
of
Ferguson's
Lane,
the
chief
attempted
to
keep

back
the
crowd,
but
the
excited
assistants
and
appren

tices
were
not
to
be
stopped,
and
knocking
him
to
one

side,
poured
in
a
torrent
after
the
lad.
It
looked
at
one

time
as
if
they
would
attempt
a
release,
but
they
con

tented
themselves
with
heartily
cheering
their
hero.

The
chief
constable
at
the
police
office
came
in
for
a

good
deal
of
hooting
and
hissing,
but
at
last
obtained
a

hearing,
and
addressing
the
crowd
said
he
had
no

wish
to
take
part
against
them
in
the
matter,
over

which
he
knew
they
felt
strongly,
but
he
must
do
his

duty,
which
was
to
keep
the
peace
of
the
city.
The

youth
was
released
after
a
few
minutes
detention,
and

borne
shoulder
high
down
the
West
Walls
by
his

delighted
companions.
Sloper,"
however,
still

remained
a
prisoner,
as
the
chief
constable
declined
to

give
him
up,
saying
they
could
get
him
in
the
morning.

The
offending
shop
keepers
closed
their
premises
about

four
o'clock.

There
will
be
a
public
meeting
next
Wednesday

night
in

with
the
movement.

question

holiday,

the
